				<div class="postbody">
				He says he will not get involved in any political process untill "the occupiers leave" with his mouth but plays politics of the most base sort with his hands.
<br />

<br />
Raising a militia is a political move.  He is not only cooperating in "politics" but is fueling the fire.  The statement is a lie when critiqued under such light. But meaning may have been lost in translation.  He is simply saying that he does not recognise the authority of the governing state.
<br />

<br />
Failing to recognise an authority is the same as inviting it to demonstrate itself.
<br />

<br />
To my experience and observation (and it is limited) the Arab has several spheres of authority: Tribal, Religious, and Secular.
<br />

<br />
Peoples actions are most heavily dependant on tribal authority.  We talk about racial this and that, really its tribal this and that.  Families stick together and the patriarchs are the ones deciding the alliance their familiy will make with other families.  Families also attend the same mosques and buy from the same market vendors. Etc etc.
<br />

<br />
In democratic situations they also vote the same way with their decisions negotiated by family elders. Its not anti democratic conspiracy, it is how they communicate and relate to each other.
<br />

<br />
When you hear Sheikh So-and-so who is a major Al Sadr aid... you should realize that the word Sheihk means he leads a family.  It is his support that gives Al-Sadr political and military power.
<br />

<br />
Clerics come and go btw.  They are a LOT like TV evangelists in thier power.  They preach and are followed by people to whom they cater too.  They also garner the following of the sheikhs who have to respond to the will of family elders and the diplomatic trust of allied families.
<br />

<br />
The real power in Iraq is at the family level and a strong nation there will have a weak national authority and strong local and regional governments.  There is little chance of that because competing families, and their societies are constantly at violent odds.<br />
