			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Well, it looks like the soap opera over there is getting more messed up. Last thursday, there was a fatwa published prohibiting muslims from assisting the US forces in iraq. US newspapers claim the fatwa was published by an iranian cleric, named haeri (who would of course be a shi'ite, which is sadr's brand of islam). Non-US newspapers claim the fatwa was published by the top iraqi sunni organization of clerics (which is the majority in iraq, and the only allowed brand in saudi). It is possible that both groups published the same thing in support of each other.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>the fatwa wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> It is forbidden for any Muslim to cooperate with the occupation forces and killing their own brothers and fellow citizens.
<br />

<br />
Iraqi police and members of civil defense (national guards) should fear God's punishment and wrath of the people as they battle with the occupation and participate in the shedding of their brothers' blood. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Since the word family means something so very different in the arab world than it does in the west, I recommend using <span style="font-style: italic">clan</span> instead. Or, when you use the word <span style="font-style: italic">family</span> in the context of middle eastern relations, you better be thinking of Hatfields, McCoys and Gotti families, and <span style="text-decoration: underline">not</span> June and Ward Cleavers. Otherwise, your mental map of what is going on, and why they act the way they do will diverge radically from reality.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.ctnow.com/news/custom/topnews/hc-iraq0816.artaug16,1,7899024.story?coll=hc-headlines-topnews" target="_blank" class="postlink"> US sample </a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=10950" target="_blank" class="postlink"> furrin sample </a>
<br />

<br />
The last time we had the place surrounded, we did what cobee was recommending: shut off the power and water and let them stink out. After more than a few days of it, all the folks were ready to kick sadr's minions for making their life miserable. To ultimately be successful in iraq, we need to make the natives want what we have, and what we can offer. Our batting average at doing that is terrible so far.<br />
